A: There are a number of great log parsers -- <a href="http://www.kaishome.com/EQCompanion" target=new>EQ Companion</a>, MEqA, EQMonk, <a href="http://eqraider.tripod.com/index.html" target=new>EQ Raider</a>, even Copeland's will work for you.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><a name="me16"></a>Q: Where should I put my starter points?</b><br>
<br>
A:It isn't going to greatly affect your life as a monk where you put these, but given the importance of getting Stamina over 100 (which prevents combat abilities decreasing in long fights) and the lack of stamina on low end gear, its probably a good idea to put as many of them as you can into Stamina.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><a name="me16a"></a>Q: Should I go for hit points over everything?</b></br><br>
A: There is long a debate on HP>AC>RESIST>STAT<p><br>
<br>
Really it is going to be situational to your primary function, so you need to really sit down and decide what it is you most often find yourself doing.<p><br>
<br>
Do you solo? AC/HP is your goal (make your HP go further and get more hp. If you are soloing mobs, then you are at a level of encounters where AC still matters)<p><br>
<br>
Do you pull? HP/Resists (espicially end game, AC begins to mean squat. You will get barraged by spells however so the more you can take and the more you resist is imperative)<p><br>
<br>
Do you small group damage? Stats/haste (in most cases you are not MT (assuming you are post 30) so your role becomes damage. All else is secondary)<p><br>
<br>
Do you raid? Resists/HP (again, MTs should be doing their job so yours is to survive all collateral damage by resisting as much as possible and having the HP to endure. Yes, this puts you well suited for end game pulling as well, and that is by design.)<p><br>
<br>
Depending on what you do, is going to be your biggest push for how you stack your monk. Additionally, where your monk is at, is also reasonably important.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><a name="me17"></a>Q: I heard that agi increases the effectiveness of dodge, block and riposte, should I focus on my agility?</b><br>
<br>
A: Increased agility appears to have two in game effects:<p><br>
(1) It slightly increases AC. Note there are critical levels for Agility though, if your AGI drops below 75 you lose a lot of AC, so don't wear anything that will reduce your AGI below this level.<br>
<br>
(2) It increases the chance that you will get a skill raise in defensive skills.<p><br>
Note: Whether agility affects AC more in a "quality" aspect as opposed to a "quantity" aspect is not known at this time, but it is a possibility.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><a name="me18"></a>Q: Strength makes me hit harder, shouldn't I put more skill into Strength?</b><br>
<br>
A: Strength has several in game effects:<br>
<br>
(1) It determines the amount of weight you can carry before becoming encumbered (This is not generally that useful for monks who generally only ever get encumbered when on their way to buy a tink bag in Sol A carrying 5250pp!)<br>
<br>
(2) It increases your average damage done per hit slightly (and it is slightly) by increasing your max damage<br>
<br>
(3) It increases your ATK.  Whether ATK increases due to strength help you hit a mob better the way ATK increases from Avatar and such do is up for debate; the general impression is that ATK increase from increased STR is a reflection of effect (2).<br>
<br>
(4) Very high strength also helps with the Blacksmithing skill.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<b><a name="me19"></a>Q: What does Dexterity do?</b><br>
<br>
A: Dexterity does NOT increase AC, i.e. it is nothing like dexterity in AD&D, which causes some confusion.<br>
<br>
Dexterity does:<br>
<br>
(1) Increase the chances that the 'Proc' on a weapon will go off.<br>
<br>
(2) Increase the chances of a skill raise in an offensive skill (Offense, 1hb, 2hb, HTH)<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Q. I'm level X, and my Z skill post 50 should cap at 252. Why isn't it going up anymore at level X?<br>
<br>
